<HEAD>Connecticut Revives Lottery System After 24-Hour Shutdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDD EVERHART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Connecticut's million-dollar-a-day
lottery was revived late Wednesday after a 24-hour shutdown
following the discovery that tickets could be bought after the
winning numbers were announced.
   The company that provided new computers for the lottery
``assured us the problems have been fixed,'' said Gregory Zieman,
assistant chief of the lottery unit of the Division of Special
Revenue.
   Lottery officials said parts of the 2,200-terminal system were
operating at 7:30 p.m. but did not know how long it would take to
get all 2,200 terminals back on line.
   The new equipment went on line Sunday. The games were suspended
Tuesday evening.
   The flaw in the system was demonstrated by two Hartford ticket
agents who saw Monday's televised drawing then played the winning
numbers, officials said. The machines gave them tickets with
numbers dated Monday instead of Tuesday.
   The pair, Jose Rodriguez and Gilberto Pardo, startled lottery
officials Tuesday when they revealed what had happened and handed
back $16,500 in checks that had just been made out in their names.
   Lottery unit spokeswoman Ann Evans said she did not know whether
there were any other such incidents. Officials say codes of winning
tickets can be checked if a problem is suspected.
   The state operates daily lottery and Play Four games and
twice-weekly Lotto games with drawings on Tuesdays and Fridays.
Tuesday's drawings were held and winners' tickets will be honored
when the system resumes operating, said J. Blaine Lewis Jr., chief
of the Special Revenue lottery unit.
   The state sells $8 million in tickets a week and has a net
weekly profit of $3 million, Lewis said.
   The mixup compounded the headaches of the Division of Special
Revenue, which was forced to shut down two jai alai frontons
because of strike by players. The state gets $55,000 a day from jai
alai wagering, officials say.
   Earlier Wednesday, some lottery agents reported unhappy
customers.
   ``They're very angry about it,'' said Richard Shoztic, manager
of Bull's Head News and Variety in Stamford.
   ``They think the store owners have something to do with it and
don't realize it's someone else's problem,'' Shoztic said. ``A few
have said they would play in New York.''
   Lewis said the contract with the company that runs the lottery
system, General Instrument Co. of Hunt Valley, Md., stipulates that
the company will be penalized when the system is down for the
amount of the state's lost profits.
   General Instrument took over the system from G-Tech Corp. of
Providence, R.I., when it was awarded a five-year, $40 million
contract in December. General Instrument's bid was $11 million
lower than G-Tech's, according to Lewis.
   General Instrument also runs the Off-Track Betting computer and
ran the state's lottery system when it was begun in the early
1970s, he said.
   General Instrument officials did not immediately return calls
placed to their Wethersfield office.
   The company also provides equipment for the 1,200-terminal
Missouri lottery. Officials there said they experienced problems
when the system went on line in 1986 but did not have to shut it
down.
</TEXT>
