<HEAD>California Lottery's Costly Computer Breakdown Investigated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUINN LOTA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A computer failure that cost the state up to
$700,000 in lost lottery ticket sales is being investigated by
specialists from the firm that set up the troubled ``Lotto 6-49''
terminals, officials said.
   Experts from GTECH, based in Providence, R.I., were to inspect
the software that caused the 3-year-old lottery's worst computer
breakdown.
   The computer crash came as the state was ending an investigation
of problems with GTECH, which has been fined $1.7 million for
computer mishaps since the company got the ``Lotto 6-49'' contract
in October 1986. A report of the investigation is due Friday, said
lottery director Chon Gutierrez.
   The computer failure Saturday night affected up to 4,700 of the
state lottery's 7,200 ``Lotto 6-49'' terminals.
   A backup system restored service to all but 120 terminals about
12 minutes later, lottery spokeswoman Susan Kossack said. ``What is
unusual is that all of the terminals on the backup system did not
come back up,'' she said.
   In spite of the outage, three players picked all six numbers
correctly to win $2 million each.
   GTECH, which operates Lotto under a $220 million five-year
contract with the state, is subject to fines for each minute of
computer lapse that occurs up to eight hours before the Wednesday
and Saturday drawings.
   GTECH faces a fine of ``close to $200,000'' as a result of the
failure, lottery computer director Joanne Hoffman told the Los
Angeles Times.
   However, Leonard G. Morrissey, GTECH's senior vice president,
told the Rocky Mountain News in Denver that his company probably
would have to pay less than $1,000 in fines for Saturday's
breakdown. GTECH is installing the system for Colorado's lottery,
which is scheduled to begin Jan. 24.
   In a related development, the San Francisco Chronicle and the
Times reported Tuesday that GTECH has been investigated by auditors
from the lottery and the state controller's office.
   The two-month investigation was prompted by allegations from two
lottery telecommunications systems analysts who contended that GTECH
concealed computer malfunctions to avoid paying the state damages
for lost Lotto revenue.
   Lew Ritter, chief of security for the state lottery, called the
allegations ``just a bunch of baloney.'' He predicted that GTECH
will be cleared of wrongdoing.
   Cynthia Nebergall, GTECH's general counsel, declined to discuss
the allegations, citing company policy.
   The two complaining workers, who have been transferred from their
jobs pending the investigation, allege that lottery officials are
covering up for GTECH.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

