<HL> Will Lotteries Win the Heart Of the South? </HL>
<AUTHOR> Eugene Carlson (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<IN> CNO </IN>
<TEXT>
   It's an old story in the gambling industry.
States where lotteries are legal invariably sell a big share of their tickets to -- and earn a major chunk of their profits from -- people who live in neighboring states where lotteries aren't allowed.

   After watching revenue dribble away to state governments next door, the lottery-free states usually come to rethink their position and start games of their own.

   This ripple effect is worth contemplating as state-sponsored games of chance begin to test the waters in the South, the last basically lottery-free region of the U.S.
Two states, both on the South's periphery, have recently approved lotteries.
Florida's lotto game, just four months old, has already run up the biggest single jackpot -- $55.2 million -- of any state lottery.
Virginia plans to begin selling lottery tickets today.

   Gaming officials and state legislators now wonder whether these lotteries will begin to erode the longstanding aversion to wagering in the core of the Bible Belt -- or whether they'll merely fuel the opposition.

   "This is an issue that would bring the church leaders out of the woodwork, and there's not many legislators that could stand that heat," says Barbara Morgan, press secretary to Georgia Gov. Joe Frank Harris.
The governor has pledged to veto any lottery bill in his state.

   In Texas, the most populous state without a lottery, a huge state-government budget deficit had lottery supporters hopeful for a while, as lotteries have proved to be potent revenue raisers.
Illinois, for example, reaped $543 million from lottery sales in the fiscal year ended June 30.

   But Texas lawmakers, who narrowly approved parimutuel betting for horse and dog tracks, have defeated a lottery bill in the past two sessions.
The state constitution bars lotteries, and changing that requires a two-thirds vote of the Legislature.

   Richard Brown, an Austin-based lobbyist who favors lotteries, thinks the racetrack backers will now join the powerful Baptist Church lobby in opposing a lottery.
"Unless there's extensive preparatory work by the (lottery) advocates, chances in the next session are bleak indeed," he says.

   Florida, meanwhile, is gladly taking the money of thousands of lottery-happy Georgians and Alabamans.
Eight of Florida's 10 top ticket sellers -- including the three biggest -- are small retailers located near the state's northern border.

   Rebecca Paul, Florida's lottery director, expects Georgia and Alabama will start lotteries.
"But," she adds, "I don't think it will happen for five years."

   Michael Jones, former Illinois lottery director and now a Chicago-based lottery consultant, believes most states will join in eventually.
He notes that Illinois started its lotto game in 1983.
Two years later, Missouri capitulated after state officials figured out that St. Louis residents were crossing the Mississippi River and buying $80 million to $100 million of Illinois lottery tickets annually.
Kansas began its lottery a year later after watching its citizens playing the new Missouri game.

   In 1964, New Hampshire was the only state with a lottery.
Since then, 27 states have followed suit.
Every state in New England, in the industrial Northeast and along the Pacific Coast has a lottery.

   The Sun Belt east of Arizona (excepting Florida) is conspicuously lottery free.
So is Utah, dominated by the Mormon Church, as well as Idaho, Wyoming and Nevada.

</TEXT>
