<HEAD>Lotto Jackpot At World Record $52 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida's Lotto jackpot increased
Wednesday to a world's record $52 million as ticket sales continued
booming.
   Sales for this week's prize were up 36 percent over Wednesday
afternoon sales last week, so officials increased the prize from
$50 million to $52 million, said Lottery Secretary Rebecca Paul.
   ``Our sales are going into orbit,'' Mrs. Paul said.
   California gave away $51.4 million in June, 21 months after
starting its computerized numbers game. Florida's Lotto began four
months ago.
   ``We have experienced unprecedented growth for a lottery state
this young,'' Mrs. Paul said.
   The $52 million jackpot is a world record, according to Terri La
Fleur, a senior editor with Gaming and Wagering Business Magazine,
a monthly trade publication based in New York City.
   The jackpot includes three weekly grand prizes, because no one
has correctly guessed the six winning numbers drawn each Saturday
night since Aug. 6. Last week's jackpot had grown to $32 million.
   Lottery officials are assuming that at least 40 million tickets
will be sold this week, to support the increase of the prize to $52
million.
   Some 32 million $1 tickets were sold last week, Mrs. Paul said.
   This week's sales of 7.8 million tickets by Wednesday afternoon
were up 36 percent over last week's sales, Mrs. Paul said. The bulk
of the sales are usually at the end of the week.
   ``The $50 million jackpot has really brought a lot of people
in,'' said Gary Harper, assistant manager of a Jiffy Store that
sell lottery tickets in Ponte Vedra Beach. ``Saturday is going to
be our big day.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>

