<HEAD>Florida Lotto Goes to $90 Million; $100 Million Possible</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida's weekly Lotto jackpot was
raised to $90 million today as sales continued at a pace that could
send the game past the $100 million mark before Saturday night's
drawing.
   The overnight $10 million increase in the prize money was
announced by Susan Nefzger, spokeswoman for the lottery.
   On Saturday, there were no winning tickets in a $50 million
lottery. The next day, the jackpot for the coming Saturday was set
at $75 million; on Monday, it was raised to $80 million.
   For the jackpot to reach $100 million, lottery officials
calculate that the state will have to sell $98 million tickets this
week. The previous record was $56 million in sales in one week, set
in April.
   Lottery Secretary Rebecca Paul said Monday's sales raced well
ahead of the record pace.
   ``It's a little crazy here right now,'' she said. ``It's a
really hard issue for us because this is so outside of the norm.''
   April Fanaken of Fort Lauderdale was playing for the first time.
   ``I have never played. I am a teacher, and all my kids all day
long have been talking about `you never know,''' she said,
referring to the slogan used by the lottery.
   Extra maintenance people were added this week to keep terminals
working across the state and additional phone lines were installed
at lottery headquarters to handle increased telephone traffic, Mrs.
Paul said.
   The national record for a lottery prize is $115 million, which
was awarded in Pennsylvania to 14 ticket-holders, some of them
individuals and some groups.
   But the U.S. record of the largest single lottery prize still
goes to Sheelah Ryan of Winter Springs, who won a Florida Lotto
jackpot of $55.1 million two years ago.
   Lotto jackpots roll over when no one picks all the winning
numbers. The Lottery Department then estimates the size of the next
week's jackpot based on sales projections.
   The odds of someone picking the winning numbers are about
one-in-14 million.
   Another concern for lottery officials is the design of the
billboards announcing jackpot estimates, which don't have space for
a nine-figure jackpot. ``The boards were not originally prepared
for the extra digi,'' said Bernie Torra, spokesman for Ackerley
Communications of Miami, lottery billboard handlers in South
Florida. ``We're working on it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>

