<HL>
   Entertainment:
   Disney Bets On
   Lottery Show
   To Hit Jackpot
   ----
   By Pauline Yoshihashi
   Staff Reporter of the Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/05/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   DIS
</CO>
<MS>
CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)
</MS>
<IN>
CASINOS AND GAMBLING (CNO)
ENTERTAINMENT AND LEISURE (ENT)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<RE>
CALIFORNIA (CA)
</RE>
<LP>
   BURBANK, Calif. -- Walt Disney Co. is about to take a spin
on creating the nation's first coast-to-coast lottery game.
   Disney's Buena Vista Television unit has teamed up with a
national group of state lottery directors to launch a
half-hour syndicated game show that would revolve around a
nationwide lottery. If all goes well, Disney and lottery
officials say the show will be on the air by the fall of 1992
and offer millions of dollars in pooled prizes every day.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Disney and the gambling officials hope to tap into the
enormous popularity of televised state lottery drawings,
which lottery experts say can draw tremendous audiences. By
teaming big daily prizes with the excitement and atmosphere
of a game show, lottery officials hope to entice new players
and re-excite those who have become somewhat bored with their
own state lotteries.
   If all 33 state and the District of Columbia lotteries
participate, lottery experts say the game could reach 85% of
the nation's population. "This will offer state lotteries a
new way to expand their business," says Peter Lynch,
president of Lottery Innovations Corp., an industry group
with representatives from 22 state lotteries. "Every lottery
in the country has expressed interest in this."
   The concept has lottery directors' juices flowing, but the
game has a way to go before it is beamed into America's
living rooms. Mr. Lynch says the partners have yet to design
the show, and they must still decide such details as how
individual state lotteries would sell the game pieces or how
prizes will be structured. Although there are federal
statutes barring the mailing of state lottery tickets and
other related acts, Mr. Lynch says, there aren't any statutes
prohibiting a national lottery-type game.
   Neither partner would disclose what the potential profits
from the venture might be or how they would be divided. If
the game did reach 85% of the population, or roughly 180
million people, Mr. Lynch says, "a realistic worst-case
scenario of 10 cents per capita per week is very, very
achievable."
   In other words, if 10% of the people play $1 a week, that
would produce $18 million a week in sales. That, in turn,
would produce a minimum of $9 million a week in prizes, or
about $1.8 million a day. In practice, the figures could
climb much higher.
   The game's most likely format, he says, is a so-called
"on-line" computerized lottery game in which game pieces
could be purchased from any of the nation's 100,000 lottery
agents. "You take home the piece and watch the show that
night, and participate in it," Mr. Lynch says. "You have a
real interest in rooting for the outcome."
   Disney officials say that player interaction will be the
key to the show's success. "We have to create an
entertainment show that stands on its own," says Randy Reiss,
executive vice president of the Walt Disney Studios. If
Disney succeeds, the game could have appeal even in states
that don't have lotteries, he adds.
   Moreover, the show could be pitched to local advertisers,
such as fast-food outlets, who could run their own games tied
to the show. A point-of-purchase game piece from a hamburger
chain, Mr. Reiss says, could get viewers to tune in in
non-lottery states.
   Since lotteries were introduced in the mid-1960s, states
have used them to help fill cash-strapped coffers. Lottomania
pumped more than $7 billion into education, senior citizens'
programs and other causes last year alone. Estimated 1990
lottery sales rose to a record $20 billion, although the
approximate 6% increase was the smallest since 1987.
   In the short term, many lottery officials say the current
recession is chipping away at customers' discretionary
income, effectively disproving the belief that gambling is
recession-proof. Sales have been affected in New York and a
number of other states, but overall the industry shows signs
of stable single-digit growth.
   Some lotteries have discovered that bigger jackpots alone
no longer guarantee player interest, but the daily prizes may
well be enough to catch the interest of rank-and-file lottery
players. On-line computerized lotteries account for the
lion's share of all lottery sales, with only about a quarter
of revenues coming from "instant" scratch-off tickets and
other niche games.
   While the televised show holds promise for lotteries, the
format that may have the greatest potential -- and that faces
the biggest hurdles -- would be a game in which players could
buy tickets and participate in other ways over the phone. A
television show tie-in would provide excitement and engage
players, things that make casino gambling popular. The
Disney-state lottery game won't involve telephones.
   "Some states are heavily involved with the possibility of
betting over the telephone and others are very far away from
it," Mr. Lynch says. "That's not something we're going to get
involved with."
</TEXT>
</DOC>

