<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Owners of six winning tickets will
split a record Florida Lotto jackpot of an estimated $105 million,
lottery officials said Sunday.
   Each of the tickets, bearing the numbers 5-6-21-34-35-45, is
worth an estimated $17.5 million, said Lottery Secretary Rebecca
Paul.
   The numbers were drawn at 11 p.m. Saturday, ending a week of
lottomania in which more than 100 million $1 tickets were sold,
sometimes at the rate of some 44,500 tickets a minute.
   The week followed four weeks in which there had been no Lotto
jackpot winner, pushing the grand prize to its near-record height.
In the history of state lotteries in the Unitd States, only a $115
million Lotto jackpot in Pennsylvania last year has been higher. In
that drawing, 14 winning tickets were sold.
   With no single ticket holder taking home the $105 million this
time, the U.S. record holder for a single winning lottery ticket
remains Sheelah Ryan of Winter Springs. She bought the only lucky
ticket in a $55.16 million Florida lottery drawing two years ago.
   Winning ticket holders in Saturday's drawing had to wait until
lottery offices opened Monday to validate the tickets and begin the
process of claiming their winnings, which will be paid off over 20
years.
   Some of the umpteen million losers had plenty to say, though.
   ``I just lost miserably,'' said Victor Morgan, who said he
bought two tickets. ``But I've wasted my money on worse things.''
He watched the drawing at Sharkey's Shrimp Bar in downtown Miami.
   Jennifer Kram, who matched just three numbers on one of her 20
tickets, ``I'm very depressed. Three isn't good enough for me. I
wanted at least $500,000.'' The three-number match will bring her a
grand total of $5.50.
   Mrs. Paul hinted at the exhaustion the week had brought lottery
officials.
   ``I think we're happy,'' she said at a midday news conference.
``I think we're glad it's over. But it's been fun and exciting.''
   She said the estimated jackpot of $105 million - ``give or take
a dollar or two'' - was based on last week's interest rates and
total sales of more than 109 million tickets. Earlier, the jackpot
was predicted to total $100 million.
   The six tickets were sold in New Smyrna Beach, Coconut Creek,
Venice, Miami, Winter Haven and Longwood.
   She said there were nearly 2 million winners overall, including
1,581 tickets with five out of the six numbers. Those players will
get $4,488 each. The 96,036 tickets with four of the six numbers
are worth $108 each. Some 1.8 million who picked three of the six
numbers will take home $5.50 each.
   The most popular combination was the simplest: 1,2,3,4,5,6. More
than 52,000 tickets had those six numbers, Mrs. Paul said.
   Had those turned out to be the winners, the per-ticket payout
would have been about $1,000, paid out in a lump sum rather than
over 20 years.
   The jackpot for this week's game, to be decided Saturday night,
was estimated at $9 million, lottery officials said.
   By law, half of every $1 spent on a Florida lottery ticket is
returned to the players in the form of prizes. At least 38{ percent
goes to education and the rest is spent on retailers and
administration.
</TEXT>
