<HEAD>Florida Lotto Jackpot Soars to $100 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jackpot fantasies are in full bloom in
Florida, where Lottery players snapped up tickets at 500 a second
in hopes of winning an estimated $100 million.
   ``I'm getting lost with all the zeroes,'' said Lottery Secretary
Rebecca Paul, who added a ninth digit Thursday to the projected
jackpot.
   No more projections will be announced before Saturday night's
televised drawing, she said.
   A $100 million jackpot would be the second largest in U.S.
history. State lottery officials doubted the jackpot would break
the $115 million record split among 14 winning tickets in
Pennsylvania's Super 7 game in April 1989.
   The number of winners will be announced Sunday. The final size
of the jackpot will not be determined until Monday, Mrs. Paul said.
   The heaviest ticket sales Thursday were reported along Florida's
borders with Georgia and Alabama. Tickets are not sold outside the
state.
   Joe Revolta and Robert Bache traveled from New Orleans to buy
10,000 tickets at $1 apiece at Groovin' Noovin's, a Pensacola
convenience store near the Alabama-Florida state line.
   ``You might not have much of a chance, but you have even less if
you don't play,'' Revolta said.
   Long-distance telephone calls poured into the state to friends
and relatives asked to buy tickets for thousands of people
attracted by the huge prize.
   Lotto mania even brought warnings from Lotto officials to spend
prudently, and a gamblers' group questioned why the lottery is not
providing money to treat compulsive gamblers.
   ``Half of the people in one Gamblers Anonymous meeting said they
were tempted because of the lottery,'' said Paul Ashe, executive
director of the Florida Council on Compulsive Gambling.
   To play the Florida Lotto game, players select six numbers from
one to 49. The winning numbers are chosen at random during a
weekly, televised drawing.
   The odds of one ticket containing all six winning numbers are
about one-in-14 million. But for every dollar spent, there was a
dream.
   ``I'd get a 200-foot yacht and staff it with chicks in bikinis
from stem to stern and go to Europe,'' said 19-year-old Ricky Ford,
a Tallahassee college student who spent $20 on tickets.
   ``First, I would help the church in any way I could, then I
would by a ticket to fly to the moon,'' said Anne Straub, 66, of
Gulf Breeze. ``I've just always wanted to go into space.''
   Bahamians carrying thousands of dollars are flying to South
Florida to buy lottery tickets to resell at a higher price back
home, the Sun-Sentinel in Fort Lauderdale reported.
   ``They come every Friday. This week they will bring $4,000 to
$5,000,'' said George Prado, who sells lottery tickets at the
Caribe Cafeteria, a Cuban restaurant near the Miami International
Airport.
</TEXT>
