<HL> Control Data Is Big Loser In Florida Lottery So Far --- A Wall Street Journal News Roundup </HL>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> CDA </CO>
<IN> CNO EDP </IN>
<TEXT>
   For Control Data Corp., the new Florida lottery has been a loser.
It already has cost the company more than $2 million.

   The Minneapolis-based computer-services concern recently won the rights to install the Florida system, and made a big deal of it in its annual report to shareholders.
It estimated potential revenue from the contract at more than $100 million.

   But when the computerized wagering system went on-line April 29, some of the 3,147 terminals installed didn't work.
"They'd be up, they'd be down, they were erratic," said Jon Peck, press secretary to Florida Gov. Bob Martinez.
"It led to a lot of confusion and dismay among those who wanted to play the games."

   As a result, the company, which has lottery contracts in six other states, agreed to forgo its first $1,460,000 payment from Florida.
Moreover, Control Data will pay the state $100,000 a month for the first half of 1989, and will throw in three new computer systems for Florida schools.

   Calling it a "glitch," a Control Data spokesman blamed some of the problem on difficulties "that always come up in dealing with the phone company and lead times."
The spokesman said that unlike other lottery contracts, Control Data had assumed responsibility for communications links between game-controlling computers and terminals scattered across the state.

</TEXT>
