<HEAD>`Who Needs $106 Million?' Says Lottery Winner Happy To Claim $17.75
Million</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from two winners,
jackpot calculated at $106.5 million. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `I
just...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who says she ``fussed at my
husband every time he bought some tickets'' was among the winners
to step forward today and claim their share of a record $106.5
million jackpot.
   Six Florida Lottery tickets matched the winning numbers drawn
Saturday night after a week of feverish buying, some of it by
people who drove or flew in from out of state or plunked down
thousands of dollars trying to improve their odds from 1 in 14
million. Two of the winners appeared at a news conference this
morning.
   Jeanne Piasecki of New Smyrna Beach said her family was
splitting the winnings. She added smilingly: ``I still don't
believe in gambling. I fussed at my husband every time he bought
some tickets.''
   Another winning ticket holder, Pat Landry of Sorrento in Lake
County, said her winning entry, bought by her daughter in Longwood,
was divided among a dozen family members and friends.
   She said she was glad their were six grand prize winners because
it helped keep the attention on her family to a minimum.
   ``Who needs $106 million?'' she commented.
   Both ticket winners said the numbers were picked at random.
   The jackpot, estimated at $105 million Sunday, was calculated
today at $106.5 million - a state record and second largest in U.S.
history. Each of the six tickets is thus worth $17.75 million over
20 years, or about $887,500 a year before taxes.
   The other four winners didn't immediately step forward. Lottery
computers show the other winning tickets were bought in Miami,
Coconut Creek, Venice and Winter Haven.
   The winners matched all six numbers drawn: 05-06-21-34-35-45.
   Some of the umpteen million losers had plenty to say, too.
   ``I just lost miserably,'' said Victor Morgan, who bought two
tickets. ``But I've wasted my money on worse things.''
   Jennifer Kram, who matched just three numbers on one of her 20
tickets, said, ``I'm very depressed. Three isn't good enough for
me. I wanted at least $500,000.'' The three-number match will bring
her a grand total of $5.50.
   The prize had snowballed for four weeks, growing with each
week's drawing every time no one won the jackpot. Only a $115
million jackpot in Pennsylvania last year has been higher. But in
that drawing, 14 winning tickets were sold.
   More than 100 million $1 tickets were sold, at up to 44,500 a
minute.
   Lottery Secretary Rebecca Paul hinted at the exhaustion the week
had brought.
   ``I think we're glad it's over,'' she said. ``But it's been fun
and exciting.''
   State economists planned to meet today to calculate how much
extra money education will reap. Education, like the rest of state
government, is facing a 5 percent spending cutback because of a
shortfall in revenue.
   By law, half of every dollar spent on a Florida lottery ticket
is paid out in prizes. At least 38.5 percent goes to education, and
the rest to retailers and administration.
   The U.S. record for a lottery prize to a single winner is held
by Florida, which awarded a woman almost $55.2 million after a
drawing two years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

